INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd2744a54-8e30-4d01-8f06-74fb330bf7e2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bicep vs Pulumi — Real Languages, Type Safety, and Unit Testing You Actually Can't Do in Bicep$escape$,
  $escape$Bicep's declarative DSL is expressive for Azure-native resources but hits a wall when logic gets complex. `for` loops require array comprehensions, conditionals are ternary-only, and there's no unit test framework — only `az deployment what-if` against live ARM. Pulumi flips this: you write real TypeScript, Python, Go, or C#, so conditionals, loops, and abstractions are first-class language constructs.

Where Bicep infers resource types from ARM schemas at author time via VS Code extension, Pulumi's `azure-native` TypeScript SDK ships full type definitions compiled from ARM specs. A misspelled property is a compile error, not a failed deployment.

Testing is where the gap is sharpest. Bicep has no unit test framework. Pulumi exposes `pulumi.runtime.setMocks()` — mock the resource graph, write Jest assertions, and validate policy compliance without touching Azure. Assert that `allowBlobPublicAccess` is `false` in CI before a single resource is provisioned.

The trade-off: Pulumi's state backend (Pulumi Cloud or self-hosted) adds operational overhead that Bicep sidesteps entirely by delegating state to ARM. For Azure-only teams with simple logic, Bicep wins on friction. Pulumi wins when your IaC needs conditionals, loops, reusable components, or testable correctness guarantees.$escape$,
  $escape$import * as pulumi from "@pulumi/pulumi";
import * as azure from "@pulumi/azure-native";

pulumi.runtime.setMocks({
  newResource: (args) => ({ id: `${args.name}-id`, state: args.inputs }),
  call: (args) => ({ outputs: args.inputs }),
});

import { storageAccount } from "./infra";

test("storage account disallows public blob access", async () => {
  const val = await new Promise<boolean>((resolve) =>
    storageAccount.allowBlobPublicAccess.apply(resolve)
  );
  expect(val).toBe(false);
});$escape$,
