INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f6575684-207f-401c-82c5-cb347e9e8b9b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Bicep IaC Testing — Checkov, PSRule, and Native Test Framework in CI$escape$,
  $escape$Bicep's native test framework (`test` keyword, Bicep ≥ 0.21) lets you validate module parameters and output shapes without deploying. `bicep test ./storage.test.bicep` compiles and evaluates `test` blocks, catching type mismatches and `assert` violations at build time — before any ARM call fires.

For static security scanning, Checkov has first-class Bicep support: `checkov --framework bicep -d .` evaluates `.bicep` source directly against CKV_AZURE rules — open NSG ports, missing `httpsOnly`, unencrypted storage accounts. Unlike tfsec (Terraform-only), Checkov parses Bicep's AST natively.

PSRule for Azure is the policy-as-code layer: `ps-rule-assert --module PSRule.Rules.Azure --input-path .` applies Azure Well-Architected Framework rules against compiled ARM output (`bicep build`) or `what-if` results. Rules like `Azure.Storage.SecureTransfer` and `Azure.AKS.MinNodeCount` fail the pipeline before a resource is touched.

Wire these as an ordered CI gate: `bicep build` → `checkov` → `ps-rule-assert` → `az deployment group what-if`. Each stage fails fast on its own signal — Checkov catches source-level misconfigurations; PSRule enforces org-wide policy compliance; `what-if` gates against unexpected ARM resource diffs.$escape$,
  $escape$# CI gate — runs before az deployment group create
bicep build main.bicep --outfile main.json

# Static security scan — Bicep AST, no ARM conversion needed
checkov --framework bicep -d . --compact --quiet

# Policy-as-code: Azure Well-Architected Framework rules
ps-rule-assert --input-path . \
  --module PSRule.Rules.Azure \
  --outcome Fail,Error

# What-if preview — validate ARM diff, no deployment
az deployment group what-if \
  --resource-group rg-staging \
  --template-file main.json \
  --parameters @params.staging.json$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
